      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Normally, SpriteKit textures ("
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sktexture"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " objects) are static, meaning that once created, their contents cannot be changed. This is important because a static image can be more efficiently managed inside the graphics hardware. However, sometimes you need to be able to update the contents of a texture dynamically. In this case, you should use a mutable texture. Because there is a performance penalty for updating the textureâ€™s contents, consider other options first. For example, you can render a texture in hardware using the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skview/1520114-texturefromnode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method and a node tree."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "To use this class, create a mutable texture using either one of its creation methods or those of its superclass. Then, when you need to update the mutable texture objectâ€™s contents, call the "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skmutabletexture/1397881-modifypixeldatawithblock"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " method. Your block is called with the location of the texture in memory. Your block should update this texture and then return."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
